{
  "chapter_number": 7,
  "chapter_title": "Looping Statements",
  "sections": [
    {
      "section_title": "Introduction",
      "keywords": ["loops", "iteration"],
      "content": "Loops are used to execute a block of code repeatedly until a specified condition becomes false."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "What is a Loop?",
      "keywords": ["definition", "loop"],
      "content": "A loop is a control structure that allows repeated execution of a set of statements."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Advantages of Loops",
      "keywords": ["advantages"],
      "content": [
        "Reduces code repetition",
        "Improves readability",
        "Saves development time",
        "Makes programs efficient"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Types of Loops",
      "keywords": ["types"],
      "content": [
        "for Loop",
        "while Loop",
        "do-while Loop"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "for Loop",
      "keywords": ["for loop"],
      "content": "The for loop is used when the number of iterations is known."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Syntax of for Loop",
      "keywords": ["for syntax"],
      "content": "for(initialization; condition; increment/decrement)\n{\n statements;\n}"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "while Loop",
      "keywords": ["while loop"],
      "content": "The while loop executes as long as the condition remains true."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Syntax of while Loop",
      "keywords": ["while syntax"],
      "content": "while(condition)\n{\n statements;\n}"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "do-while Loop",
      "keywords": ["do while"],
      "content": "The do-while loop executes the loop body at least once before checking the condition."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Syntax of do-while Loop",
      "keywords": ["do while syntax"],
      "content": "do\n{\n statements;\n}\nwhile(condition);"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Nested Loops",
      "keywords": ["nested loops"],
      "content": "A loop inside another loop is called a nested loop."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Infinite Loop",
      "keywords": ["infinite loop"],
      "content": "A loop that never terminates because its condition always remains true."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "break Statement",
      "keywords": ["break"],
      "content": "The break statement immediately terminates the loop."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "continue Statement",
      "keywords": ["continue"],
      "content": "The continue statement skips the current iteration and moves to the next iteration."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Example Program",
      "keywords": ["example"],
      "content": "#include <stdio.h>\n\nint main()\n{\n int i;\n for(i=1;i<=5;i++)\n {\n printf(\"%d \",i);\n }\n return 0;\n}"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Applications",
      "keywords": ["applications"],
      "content": [
        "Pattern Printing",
        "Searching",
        "Sorting",
        "Data Processing",
        "Mathematical Calculations"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "summary": [
    "Loops execute code repeatedly.",
    "for loop is used when iterations are known.",
    "while loop checks condition before execution.",
    "do-while executes at least once.",
    "break terminates loops.",
    "continue skips an iteration."
  ]
}
